If you take too much (overdose)

Immediately telephone your doctor or the National Poisons Centre (telephone 0800 POISON or 0800 764 766), or go to Accident and Emergency at your nearest hospital, if you think that you or anyone else may have taken too much IBUPROFEN. Do this even if there are no signs of discomfort or poisoning. You may need urgent medical attention.

If you take too much IBUPROFEN you may:

• feel sick or vomit;
• have stomach pain;
• have convulsions;
• have a slow or fast heartbeat;
• have ringing in your ears;
• feel drowsy;
• feel dizzy or even become unconscious.
• vomit blood or material that looks like coffee grounds;
• bleed from the rectum (back passage), black sticky bowel motions (stools) or bloody diarrhoea.
• have a headache and/or experience rapid, uncontrollable movements of the eyes.

Overdosing may result in problems with your kidneys and low potassium levels in your blood.

If you take too much (overdose)

Immediately telephone your doctor or the National Poisons Centre (telephone 0800 POISON or 0800 764 766), or go to accident and emergency at your nearest hospital, if you think that you or anyone else may have taken too much Brufen Extra. Do this even if there are no signs of discomfort or poisoning. You may need urgent medical attention.

Taking too many Brufen Extra tablets can lead to delayed, serious liver and renal damage.

If you take too much Brufen Extra you may:

• pale appearance;
• feel sick or vomiting;
• have stomach pain;
• have convulsions;
• have a slow or fast heartbeat;
• very slow breathing;
• have ringing in your ears;
• feel drowsy;
• feeling dizzy or even becoming unconscious;
• vomit blood or material that looks like coffee grounds;
• bleed from the rectum (back passage), black sticky bowel motions (stools) or bloody diarrhoea;
• lack of co-ordination;
• slurred speech.
